'''Simantra''' (or [[semantron]] or in Romanian [[Toacă]]) is an [[Eastern Orthodox]] [[percussion instrument]] used in [[liturgy|liturgical service]]<ref>[[Ormonde Maddock Dalton|Dalton, Ormonde Maddock]] (1903). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=55dAAAAAYAAJ&dq=simantra&source=gbs_navlinks_s A Guide to the Early Christian and Byzantine Antiquities in the Department of British and Mediæval Antiquities]'', p.96 & 104. British Museum. Dept. of British and Mediaeval Antiquities and Ethnography.</ref> and is either a wooden or metal slab or bar that is mounted or suspended and struck with a [[percussion mallet|mallet]]. The Simantra has been used by classical composers including [[Iannis Xenakis]] (''[[Persephassa (Xenakis)|Persephassa]]'') and in [[Michael Gordon (composer)|Michael Gordon]]'s ''[http://www.michaelgordonmusic.com/music/timber Timber]'' (2011).<ref>"[http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/6683 Dusted Reviews: Michael Gordon - Timber]", ''DustedMagazine.com'' and "[http://epmusic.wordpress.com/2011/08/09/review-michael-gordons-timber/ Review: Michael Gordon’s Timber]", ''Endless Possibilities''.</ref> A Simantra is rich in [[overtone]]s compared to the bars of percussion instruments such as a [[marimba]] or [[xylophone]], where the [[fundamental frequency|fundamental]] is primary. The [[timbre|tone]] changes based on how near or far from the nodes the mallets strike the board.
For the history of the instrument, see the much more detailed article for the [[Semantron]].
